   =20
      Screen time
   =20
 =20
I must say that, as a long-time observer of U.S. regulation and an outsider=
 to China, I have enjoyed the variety and creativity of China=E2=80=99s reg=
ulatory crackdown on its various tech companies over the last few months. I=
n the U.S., if regulators get annoyed with for-profit education companies, =
they will do things like mandate additional disclosures or fiddle with the =
eligibility requirements for federal student loans. In China, when regulato=
rs got annoyed with for-profit education companies, they=C2=A0told them to =
become non-profits. =E2=80=9CYou can keep doing your business, but you can=
=E2=80=99t make any money from it anymore.=E2=80=9D If you are used to the =
U.S. system it just seems wild.Or if U.S. regulators decided that kids were=
 playing too many video games, they would mandate warning labels or ask for=
 voluntary restrictions on advertising or something. In China:Chinese gamin=
g stocks listed in the U.S. came under pressure once again on Monday after =
regulators in Beijing cut back the amount of time children can play online =
each week to just three hours. ...The latest rules will only allow gaming p=
latforms to offer services to minors from 8 p.m. to 9 p.m. on Fridays, week=
ends and public holidays, according to state news agency Xinhua, which cite=
d a release by the National Press and Publication Administration.=C2=A0Obvi=
ously there are some disadvantages to having a legal system like this! But =
it is interesting to observe from the outside.It is hard, for me, not to th=
ink of this crackdown in the context of the U.S. Securities and Exchange Co=
mmission=E2=80=99s efforts to make online retail trading at Robinhood Marke=
ts Inc. less fun. It seems fairly clear that the SEC thinks that=C2=A0frequ=
ent risky retail trading is bad, bad for the wallets of Robinhood=E2=80=99s=
 customers and for the integrity of markets and for just, like, stocks go u=
p 1,000% in a week and nobody can explain why and the whole thing looks sor=
t of dumb and Congress asks the SEC about it and the SEC has no satisfying =
explanation. But the SEC can=E2=80=99t just say =E2=80=9Call this retail tr=
ading is dumb, stop it.=E2=80=9D It can=E2=80=99t say that because that is =
sort of impolitic and un-American; if American freedom means anything, it m=
eans the unfettered right to day-trade stocks on your phone for free. It al=
so can=E2=80=99t say that because it doesn=E2=80=99t really have the regula=
tory apparatus to do it. You can=E2=80=99t, like, ban retail trading.And so=
 the SEC does things like issue a request for comment asking if =E2=80=9Cbr=
oker-dealers=E2=80=9D (a neutral way to say =E2=80=9CRobinhood=E2=80=9D) us=
e =E2=80=9Cdark patterns=E2=80=9D in their =E2=80=9Cdigital engagement prac=
tices,=E2=80=9D because presumably if they catch the dark patterns they can=
 force Robinhood to be less engaging. Or the SEC=E2=80=99s chairman talks a=
bout banning payment for order flow, because if Robinhood can=E2=80=99t get=
 paid for its orders maybe it will have to charge commissions and so become=
 less fun and engaging.=C2=A0Imagine the Chinese approach! Just have the SE=
C announce a new rule saying =E2=80=9Cyou can only play Robinhood three hou=
rs a week.=E2=80=9D It would be a simpler approach. Though those three hour=
s in the market=C2=A0would be wild.
