<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">GameStop and the S&amp;P</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Every so often a weird stock goes up a=
 lot, and it becomes so valuable that it qualifies for=C2=A0the S&amp;P 500=
, the main index of U.S. large-cap stocks, and then people write articles t=
hat are like =E2=80=9Coh no all the index funds are being forced to buy thi=
s weird stock at a huge valuation that makes no sense.=E2=80=9D This does n=
ot bother me very much: The whole point of an index fund is that you buy al=
l the stocks at whatever their market prices are, rather than trying to pre=
dict which ones are over- or undervalued. If you index, sometimes you will =
buy stocks that are overvalued, but, crucially,=C2=A0<em>you will do this l=
ess often than most fundamental active investors do</em>. The fundamental a=
ctive investors, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2=
4919743.261230/aHR0cHM6Ly93ZWIuc3RhbmZvcmQuZWR1L353ZnNoYXJwZS9hcnQvYWN0aXZl=
L2FjdGl2ZS5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB888a34bf" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" i=
temscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impo=
rtant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-botto=
m-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">remember</a>,=C2=A0<em>underperfor=
m the index in aggregate</em>. So when they go around saying =E2=80=9Chahah=
a the index funds are so dumb for buying this crazy overvalued stock,=E2=80=
=9D they are wrong slightly more often than they are right.</p><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">Still I want to propose a solution to this very small prob=
lem, which is that there should be two S&amp;P 500 indexes, like, the S&amp=
;P 490 Normal Companies Index and the S&amp;P 510 Index With Some Weird Com=
panies. You take your <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cl=
