</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px=
 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Somebody (the board of directors,=
 the chief executive officer, a division head)=C2=A0at some company is doin=
g something.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Someone above that pe=
rson in the theoretical legal hierarchy of control decides to fire them. Th=
e shareholders vote out the board, the board fires the CEO, the CEO fires t=
he division head, whatever.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The fi=
red person says =E2=80=9Cno thank you,=E2=80=9D changes the locks on the co=
mpany=E2=80=99s front door (or the password on its Twitter account), and ke=
eps doing what they were doing.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Th=
e people=C2=A0who fired them are puzzled.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom=
: 5px;">Everyone goes to court.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Fo=
r a while there are in some sense two companies, one run by the fired perso=
n and the other run by the people who did the firing, and employees and cus=
tomers have to choose which one to be loyal to.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-=
bottom: 5px;">It=E2=80=99s all sort of fun and confusing.</li></ol><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That=E2=80=99s usually as far as it gets? I write abou=
t the situation once or twice, I make some jokes,=C2=A0and then the tension=
 resolves. A court will usually sort it out quickly enough. And anyway ther=
e are powerful incentives to settle. The company is <em>valuable</em>; its =
network of relationships and contracts and customers and suppliers and empl=
oyees is worth a lot of money. If you split it into confusing infighting, a=
 lot of value is destroyed. Better for everyone to settle the fight quickly=
, before the value can be destroyed. If you go on fighting too long, you mi=
ght end up controlling all the value in the company, but that value might h=
ave gone to zero.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A really good who-control=
s-a-company story that we <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.co=
m/click/24919743.261230/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGl=
jbGVzLzIwMjAtMDYtMjQvdGltZS10by1kby1hY3RpdmlzbS1pbi1yZXZlcnNl/607f07ceef4b8=
524a319a23cB531ad1e4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">talked about last June</a> was Arm China. Arm Ltd. is a semico=
nductor company. It launched a joint venture in China, generally called =E2=
=80=9CArm China.=E2=80=9D Arm had a large (minority) ownership stake and co=
ntrol of the joint venture. Arm and a few of the other investors =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0who together owned a majority of the stock and so seemed to have the =
legal right to make corporate decisions =E2=80=94=C2=A0decided to fire the =
CEO of Arm China, Allen Wu. And the board, controlled by those shareholders=
, voted 7 to 1 to fire him. But Wu decided he=E2=80=99d rather not be fired=
. He seems to have retained the loyalty of the Chinese employees; also, cru=
cially, he had control of the corporate seals, which are necessary in China=
 to ratify corporate actions. I made some jokes:</p><blockquote><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">To fire the CEO, they need the stamp, but the CEO has the=
 stamp, so he has to approve his firing, and he won=E2=80=99t do it. Oh sur=
e sure sure the shareholders have formal ownership rights, they =E2=80=9Cco=
uld go through the courts,=E2=80=9D but in practice the seal is the reality=
 of control and the ownership is a mere abstraction. I hope they=E2=80=99re=
 sending a team of cat burglars to get the seal back.</p></blockquote><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There were a bunch of good corporate-seal stories o=
ut of China that summer; <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com=
/click/24919743.261230/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGlj=
bGVzLzIwMjAtMDctMTQvZXZlcnlvbmUtd2FudHMtYS1ibGFuay1jaGVjaw/607f07ceef4b8524=
a319a23cBf8c0f1bd" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color=
: #ccc;">later I wrote</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If =
you control a company, you do so as a purely social fact: A bunch of people=
 who work there will treat you as the boss, a bunch of customers will treat=
 you as their counterparty, the legal system will treat you as a controller=
. Everything that you think gives you control=E2=80=94share certificates an=
d board resolutions and a big desk=E2=80=94is just a symbol of those intang=
ible social facts. But if you concentrate enough symbolism in one more or l=
ess arbitrary physical object, that physical object will become almost as g=
ood as the social fact itself, and you=E2=80=99ll end up sleeping with it u=
nder your pillow.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Well, it=E2=
=80=99s been more than a year; how are things at Arm China? This April, <a =
href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24919743.261230/aHR0c=
HM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDQtMDkvYXJtLWJhdHRs=
ZS13aXRoLWNoaW5hLWNlby1lc2NhbGF0ZXMtY29tcGxpY2F0aW5nLXNvZnRiYW5rLXNhbGU/607=
f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb5cb2461" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsco=
pe" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; bac=
kground-color: #ccc;">Bloomberg reported</a> that =E2=80=9CThe battle for c=
ontrol of Arm Ltd.=E2=80=99s China business is escalating with new lawsuits=
 aimed at keeping the unit=E2=80=99s controversial chief executive in power=
, further complicating SoftBank Group Corp.=E2=80=99s efforts to sell the b=
usiness to Nvidia Corp.=E2=80=9D And here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/24919743.261230/aHR0cHM6Ly9zZW1pYW5hbHlzaXMuY29t=
L3RoZS1zZW1pY29uZHVjdG9yLWhlaXN0LW9mLXRoZS1jZW50dXJ5LWFybS1jaGluYS1oYXMtZ29=
uZS1jb21wbGV0ZWx5LXJvZ3VlLW9wZXJhdGluZy1hcy1hbi1pbmRlcGVuZGVudC1jb21wYW55LX=
dpdGgtdGhlaXItb3duLWlwLw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa2d649a2" itemprop=3D"Sto=
ryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: n=
one !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bor=
der-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Dylan Patel at SemiAnalys=
is</a>=C2=A0last Friday:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Recent=
ly, they gave a presentation to the industry about rebranding their own IP,=
 extending it by developing more, and emphasizing that they are striking th=
eir own independently operated path. ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Th=
is is the tech heist of the century. ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">De=
spite formally being fired, Allen Wu has remained in power. He ousted execu=
tives that were loyal to Arm. He has even hired security paid for by Arm Ch=
ina that reports to him. This security has kept Arm out of the Arm China of=
fices. Allen Wu has aggressively taken over the firm and is operating it ho=
w he sees fit. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This leads us to t=
he present day, where Arm China held an event at which they formally declar=
ed their independence. They proclaimed that [Arm China]=C2=A0is China=E2=80=
=99s largest CPU IP supplier. It was born from Arm, but is an independently=
 operated, Chinese owned company.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">Ah! Well! Cool! I mean=C2=A0<em>in general=C2=A0</em>it is value-destru=
ctive to have a drawn-out legal battle about who is in charge of the compan=
y, especially where (as here) the parent company refuses to transfer more i=
ntellectual property to the joint venture. But if you can take the company =
and run with it and develop your own IP and freeze out your shareholders en=
tirely then maybe that=C2=A0<em>is=C2=A0</em>better than just being fired? =
(=E2=80=9CWu, a Chinese-born U.S. citizen, pulled back from signing settlem=
ent agreements worth tens of millions of dollars if he would leave the comp=
any,=E2=80=9D Bloomberg reported in April, presumably because staying was w=
orth more?)=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t know, you=
 don=E2=80=99t see too many stories like this? A company that spins off fro=
m another company not through a series of corporate transactions but throug=
h sheer force of will of its CEO? Who=C2=A0<em>owns=C2=A0</em>it? Like what=
 happens if Wu runs Arm China for a decade or two, makes it a profitable in=
dependent company, and then sells it in a cash merger? Who gets the cash? D=
oes Arm get a check from its long-estranged corporate child? Or does Wu say=
 to the acquirer, well, look, never mind what the shareholder records say, =
this is my company so write the check to me?</p>
